    <h2 id="how-it-works">How English Becomes Japanese</h2>
    <p>English words undergo predictable pronunciation changes in Japanese. Consonant clusters get broken up with vowels: &quot;strike&quot; becomes ストライク (sutoraiku). Final consonants get a vowel added: &quot;cat&quot; becomes キャット (kyatto). L becomes R: &quot;lemon&quot; becomes レモン (remon). &quot;Th&quot; becomes s/z: &quot;thank you&quot; becomes サンキュー (sankyuu). Long vowels use ー: &quot;cake&quot; becomes ケーキ (keeki).</p>

