    <h2 id="false-friends">False Friends: Words That Trick You</h2>
    <p><strong>マンション</strong> (manshon) means apartment, not mansion. <strong>スマート</strong> (sumaato) often means slim or stylish, not smart. <strong>バイキング</strong> (baikingu) means buffet, not Viking. <strong>ナイーブ</strong> (naiibu) means sensitive, not naive. <strong>カンニング</strong> (kanningu) means cheating on a test, not cunning.</p>

    <h2 id="decode">How to Decode New Words</h2>
    <p>When you see unfamiliar katakana: read it aloud slowly, listen for the English hiding inside, then reverse the pronunciation rules — remove extra vowels, try L instead of R, restore consonant clusters. Practice with our <a href="/japanese/tools/katakana-chart/">Katakana Chart</a> and test yourself with the <a href="/japanese/tools/kana-quiz/">Kana Quiz</a>.</p>

